text: Welcome back to the Medito Beginner Sessions. We all feel negative emotions at times. Sometimes they can have a big impact on our lives. Whether it's stress, jealousy, anger, or fear, sometimes it can all feel a bit overwhelming. It can be tempting to try to push these feelings away or to distract yourself in order to escape the negativity. But more often than not, this approach only brings temporary relief. Mindfulness can change your relationship with negative emotions, helping you to process them in a healthier way. Mindfulness allows you to become aware of thoughts and feelings as they arise. It also teaches you how to observe negative emotions without becoming too attached to them. With practice, you will learn how to use mindfulness to choose which thoughts you give your attention to and which thoughts you will acknowledge but let pass. By developing a healthier relationship with our emotions, our negative thoughts will begin to have less effect on our daily lives. Now, let's start today's session. Make yourself comfortable in an upright position. With eyes closed, breathe in deeply and hold the breath for a few seconds before releasing. Repeat this a couple of times. While maintaining an alert position, let your muscles relax. Without focusing on any part in particular, take notice of any bodily sensations as they appear. Focus on your intention for a moment. Do you want to become more mindful of your emotions? Or less reactive when something upsets you? Whatever your goal is, be clear in your intention. Now, bring your attention to the breath. Let go if you're controlling it. And follow its natural rhythm. Pay very close attention to each in-breath and each out-breath. Try to notice every detail. You can count each breath. Or you might prefer to just watch them come and go. It's up to you. You can count each in-breath. You can count each in-breath. You can count each in-breath. You can count each in-breath.
